 in Southern California, Columbia in Maryland, and The Woodlands in the suburbs of Houston, Texas. Based on new research and interviews with developers, designers, and residents, Ann Forsyth traces the evolution, the successes, and the shortcomings of these experiments in urban innovation. Where they succeeded, in areas such as community identity and open space preservation, they provide support for current "smart growth" proposals. Where they did not, in areas such as housing affordability and transportation choices, they offer important insights for today's planners, designers, developers, civic leaders, and others interested in incorporating new forms of development into their designs.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aCity planningzCaliforniazIrvine. 0aCity planningzMarylandzColumbia. 0aCity planningzTexaszWoodlands. 0aPlanned communitieszUnited StatesvCase studies. 7aARCHITECTURE / History / General.2bisacsh  a1960s.  a1970s.  aarchitecture planning.  acity planning.  acivic leaders.  acolumbia.  acommunity identity.  aenvironmental preservation.  ahousing designers.  ahousing developers.  ahousing experiments.  ahousing plans.  ahouston.  airvine ranch.  amaryland.  aneighborhood planning.  anew community movement.  anonfiction.  aplanned communities.  asocial communities.  asouthern california.  asuburban communities.  asuburban landscape.  asuburbia.  atexas.  athe woodlands.  aurban innovation.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertDG and UP eBook Package 2000-2015z978311063872108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of California Press Backlist Package 2000-2013z97831106904220 cprintz978052024166440uhttps://doi.org/10.1525/978052093791840uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780520937918423Coveruhttps://